      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1759926750,
      "post_id" : 79785252,
      "comment_id" : 140783880,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "<code>test</code> just delegates to the backing method reference / lambda. So a predicate created from <code>&quot;my string literal&quot;::equals</code> (or alternatively, <code>s -&gt; &quot;my string literal&quot;.equals(s)</code> will be almost as performant as calling <code>.equals</code> directly. You&#39;ll have to perform millions of calls to see the difference. Likewise, <code>MY_PATTERN_CONSTANT.asPredicate()</code> will be almost as performant as calling <code>MY_PATTERN_CONSTANT.matcher(s).find()</code>, because that&#39;s what&#39;s being called. If you need <code>matches</code> then use <code>s -&gt; MY_PATTERN_CONSTANT.matcher(s).matches()</code>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1211967,
        "reputation" : 9964,
        "user_id" : 1180351,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/pKB8y.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Rob Spoor",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1180351/rob-spoor"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 31180,
        "reputation" : 29752,
        "user_id" : 85421,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/kKvXH.gif?s=256",
