      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1759926836,
      "post_id" : 79785252,
      "comment_id" : 140783882,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@user85421 <code>String,matches</code> always creates a new <code>Pattern</code>, and should therefore only be used if the regex is dynamic. If it&#39;s fixed, always create a <code>private static final Pattern</code> constant and use <code>PATTERN_CONSTANT.matcher(s).matches()</code> instead."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1211967,
        "reputation" : 9964,
        "user_id" : 1180351,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/pKB8y.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Rob Spoor",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1180351/rob-spoor"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1759926950,
      "post_id" : 79785252,
      "comment_id" : 140783889,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "The following is not thread-safe (Pattern is, Matcher isn&#39;t), but it would look like this: <code>private static final Pattern PATTERN = Pattern.compile(&quot;...&quot;); private static final Matcher MATCHER = PATTERN.matcher(&quot;&quot;);</code> for the declarations, then <code>MATCHER.reset(&quot;actual string&quot;)</code> and <code>MATCHER.matches()</code>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1211967,
        "reputation" : 9964,
        "user_id" : 1180351,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/pKB8y.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Rob Spoor",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1180351/rob-spoor"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1759927069,
      "post_id" : 79785252,
      "comment_id" : 140783893,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "That&#39;s the inverse: it will treat that string literal as the string to match, and the argument as the regex. It&#39;s the same as <code>s -&gt; &quot;literal&quot;.matches(s)</code>. And replacing an explicit <code>Pattern</code> with <code>String.matches</code> is never an optimization, as the latter creates a new <code>Pattern</code> for every invocation."
