    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1759918153,
    "last_edit_date" : 1759918153,
    "creation_date" : 1759913672,
    "answer_id" : 79785252,
    "question_id" : 79785244,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You could use a regex-based approach like you suggested. Instead of an array of <code>String</code>s, use an array of <code>Pattern</code>s (i.e. regexes).</p>\n<p>For strings that you want to match literally, use <code>Pattern.quote</code> to create a &quot;literal&quot; regex. For everything else, write an appropriate regex to match the desired text.</p>\n<pre><code>private static final Pattern[] REPLIES = {\n        Pattern.compile(Pattern.quote(&quot;Step is done: 123,345&quot;)),\n        Pattern.compile(Pattern.quote(&quot;+OK&quot;)),\n        Pattern.compile(&quot;Process \\\\d+ finished&quot;)\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>if</code> condition can be changed to</p>\n<pre><code>if(REPLIES[i].matcher(reply).matches())\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<p>An alternative to a <code>Pattern</code> array is <code>List&lt;Predicate&lt;String&gt;&gt;</code>. You can write exactly what you want the <code>if</code> condition to be for a given reply using a lambda expression.</p>\n<pre><code>private static final Pattern THIRD_REPLY_PATTERN = Pattern.compile(&quot;Process \\\\d+ finished&quot;);\nprivate static final List&lt;Predicate&lt;String&gt;&gt; REPLIES = Arrays.asList( // use List.of(...) on Java 9+\n        s -&gt; s.equals(&quot;Step is done: 123,345&quot;),\n        s -&gt; s.equals(&quot;+OK&quot;),\n        s -&gt; THIRD_REPLY_PATTERN.matcher(s).matches()\n);\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>if</code> condition would <code>test</code> the predicate</p>\n<pre><code>if (REPLIES.get(i).test(reply))\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
